    {
        "id": "mole-concept-advanced-sec4-chem",
        "title": "Advanced Mole Calculations",
        "title_zh": "高级摩尔计算",
        "gradeLevel": "sec4",
        "tag": "Chemistry",
        "tag_zh": "化学",
        "description": "Complex stoichiometry, limiting reagents, and percentage yield",
        "description_zh": "复杂化学计量、限制试剂和百分产率",
        "objectives": [
            "Perform multi-step stoichiometric calculations",
            "Identify limiting reagents and calculate theoretical yield",
            "Calculate percentage yield and purity"
        ],
        "objectives_zh": [
            "进行多步化学计量计算",
            "识别限制试剂并计算理论产量",
            "计算百分产率和纯度"
        ],
        "sections": [
            {
                "id": "limiting-reagent",
                "type": "text",
                "title": "Limiting Reagent & Excess",
                "title_zh": "限制试剂与过量",
                "content": "**Limiting Reagent** is the reactant that is completely consumed first, limiting the amount of product formed.\n\n**Excess Reagent** is the reactant that remains after the reaction is complete.\n\n**Why It Matters:**\n- In real reactions, reactants are rarely in perfect stoichiometric ratios\n- The limiting reagent determines the **maximum product** that can form\n- Important for cost efficiency in industrial chemistry (Jurong Island)\n\n**Steps to Find Limiting Reagent:**\n\n1. **Write balanced equation**\n2. **Calculate moles of each reactant**\n3. **Use stoichiometry** to find how much product each reactant could make\n4. **Reactant that makes LEAST product** is limiting\n5. **Calculate actual product** based on limiting reagent\n6. **Calculate excess remaining** (optional)\n\n**Example: Making Water**\n$$2H_2 + O_2 \\rightarrow 2H_2O$$\n\nGiven:\n- 4.0 g H₂\n- 16.0 g O₂\n\nWhich is limiting?\n\n**Step 1: Calculate moles**\n- Moles H₂ = 4.0/2 = 2.0 mol\n- Moles O₂ = 16.0/32 = 0.5 mol\n\n**Step 2: Check stoichiometry**\nFrom equation: 2 mol H₂ reacts with 1 mol O₂\n\n- 2.0 mol H₂ needs: 2.0/2 = 1.0 mol O₂\n- But we only have 0.5 mol O₂\n\n**O₂ is limiting** (not enough!)\n\n**Step 3: Calculate H₂O produced**\nBased on O₂ (limiting):\n- 1 mol O₂ → 2 mol H₂O\n- 0.5 mol O₂ → 1.0 mol H₂O\n- Mass = 1.0 × 18 = **18 g H₂O**\n\n**Step 4: Calculate H₂ remaining**\n- H₂ used: 0.5 × 2 = 1.0 mol\n- H₂ remaining: 2.0 - 1.0 = 1.0 mol = **2.0 g H₂ excess**\n\n**Singapore Industrial Example:**\n**Ammonia Production (Haber Process)**\n$$N_2 + 3H_2 \\rightarrow 2NH_3$$\n\nIf using 100 kg N₂ and 20 kg H₂:\n\n- Moles N₂ = 100,000/28 = 3571 mol\n- Moles H₂ = 20,000/2 = 10,000 mol\n\n- 3571 mol N₂ needs: 3571 × 3 = 10,713 mol H₂\n- But only have 10,000 mol H₂\n\n**H₂ is limiting**\n\n- NH₃ produced: (10,000/3) × 2 = 6667 mol\n- Mass = 6667 × 17 = **113 kg NH₃** (theoretical)\n\n**Excess N₂:** 3571 - (10,000/3) = 238 mol = 6.7 kg\n\n**Key Point:** Industries often use excess of cheaper reactant to ensure expensive reactant is fully consumed.\n\n**Percentage Yield:**\n\n$$\\text{Percentage Yield} = \\frac{\\text{Actual Yield}}{\\text{Theoretical Yield}} \\times 100\\%$$\n\n**Reasons for < 100%:**\n1. **Incomplete reaction** (equilibrium)\n2. **Side reactions** (unwanted products)\n3. **Product lost** during transfer/purification\n4. **Measurement errors**\n5. **Impure reactants**\n\n**Example:**\nTheoretical yield: 113 kg NH₃\nActual yield: 85 kg NH₃\n\nPercentage yield = (85/113) × 100% = **75%**\n\nThis is typical for Haber process under industrial conditions.\n\n**Atom Economy:**\n\n$$\\text{Atom Economy} = \\frac{\\text{Mass of Desired Product}}{\\text{Total Mass of Reactants}} \\times 100\\%$$\n\n**Green Chemistry** aims for high atom economy (minimize waste)\n\n**Example: Making Aspirin**\n$$C_7H_6O_3 + C_4H_6O_3 \\rightarrow C_9H_8O_4 + C_2H_4O_2$$\n\nMolar masses:\n- Salicylic acid: 138 g/mol\n- Acetic anhydride: 102 g/mol\n- **Aspirin: 180 g/mol** (desired)\n- Acetic acid: 60 g/mol (byproduct)\n\nAtom economy = 180/(138+102) × 100% = **75%**\n\n**Singapore Petrochemical Industry:**\n- Optimize limiting reagent to maximize profit\n- Monitor percentage yield for quality control\n- Design processes with high atom economy\n- Recycle excess reactants when possible"
            },
            {
                "id": "solution-stoichiometry",
                "type": "text",
                "title": "Solution Stoichiometry & Titrations",
                "title_zh": "溶液化学计量与滴定",
                "content": "**Concentration** is the amount of solute dissolved in a given amount of solvent/solution.\n\n**Molarity (M):** Moles of solute per liter of solution\n\n$$M = \\frac{n}{V} = \\frac{\\text{moles}}{\\text{volume (L)}}$$\n\nor\n\n$$n = M \\times V$$\n\n**Units:** mol/L or mol/dm³ or M\n\n**Example:**\n0.5 mol NaCl in 2 L water\n\nMolarity = 0.5/2 = **0.25 M**\n\n**Dilution:**\nAdding more solvent decreases concentration\n\n$$M_1V_1 = M_2V_2$$\n\n- M₁, V₁ = initial molarity and volume\n- M₂, V₂ = final molarity and volume\n- **Moles remain constant** during dilution\n\n**Example: Singapore Lab**\nDilute 50 mL of 2.0 M HCl to 200 mL\n\nM₂ = M₁V₁/V₂ = (2.0 × 50)/200 = **0.5 M**\n\n**Stoichiometry with Solutions:**\n\n**Steps:**\n1. Calculate moles from M and V: n = M × V\n2. Use balanced equation ratios\n3. Calculate moles of product\n4. Convert to mass or concentration as needed\n\n**Example: Neutralization**\n$$HCl + NaOH \\rightarrow NaCl + H_2O$$\n\n25 mL of 0.10 M HCl reacts with 0.20 M NaOH. Volume NaOH needed?\n\n**Moles HCl:** n = 0.10 × 0.025 = 0.0025 mol\n\n**Stoichiometry:** 1:1 ratio\n\n**Moles NaOH needed:** 0.0025 mol\n\n**Volume NaOH:** V = n/M = 0.0025/0.20 = **0.0125 L = 12.5 mL**\n\n**Titration** is a technique to determine the concentration of an unknown solution using a solution of known concentration (standard solution).\n\n**Apparatus:**\n- **Burette:** Deliver known volumes of titrant (usually 50 mL capacity)\n- **Pipette:** Measure exact volume of analyte (e.g., 25.0 mL)\n- **Conical flask:** Contains analyte + indicator\n- **Indicator:** Shows endpoint (phenolphthalein, methyl orange)\n\n**Procedure:**\n1. **Rinse** burette with titrant, pipette with analyte\n2. **Fill** burette with titrant (record initial volume)\n3. **Pipette** exact volume of analyte into flask\n4. **Add** 2-3 drops of indicator\n5. **Titrate:** Add titrant slowly with swirling\n6. **Endpoint:** Color change indicates neutralization complete\n7. **Record** final burette volume\n8. **Repeat** for concordant results (within 0.1 mL)\n\n**Calculations:**\n\n$$\\frac{M_1V_1}{n_1} = \\frac{M_2V_2}{n_2}$$\n\nwhere n₁ and n₂ are stoichiometric coefficients\n\n**Example: Finding Unknown HCl Concentration**\n\n25.0 mL HCl titrated with 0.10 M NaOH\nVolume NaOH used: 23.5 mL\n\n$$HCl + NaOH \\rightarrow NaCl + H_2O$$\n\n(1:1 ratio)\n\n$$M_{HCl} \\times 25.0 = M_{NaOH} \\times 23.5$$\n\n$$M_{HCl} \\times 25.0 = 0.10 \\times 23.5$$\n\n$$M_{HCl} = \\frac{2.35}{25.0} = 0.094 M$$\n\n**Singapore Practical Applications:**\n\n**1. Water Treatment (NEWater/PUB):**\n- Titrations monitor pH and chemical concentrations\n- Ensure safe drinking water (pH 6.5-8.5)\n\n**2. Quality Control (Food Industry):**\n- Vinegar acidity (acetic acid content)\n- Milk freshness (lactic acid from bacteria)\n- Vitamin C content in fruit juices\n\n**3. Environmental Monitoring (NEA):**\n- River/reservoir water quality\n- Industrial discharge compliance\n- Acid rain monitoring\n\n**4. Pharmaceuticals:**\n- Drug purity and concentration\n- Active ingredient content\n\n**5. School Laboratories:**\n- O-Level practical exams\n- Learning analytical techniques\n\n**Common Titration Types:**\n\n**Acid-Base:**\n- HCl vs NaOH (strong-strong)\n- CH₃COOH vs NaOH (weak acid-strong base)\n\n**Redox:**\n- KMnO₄ vs Fe²⁺ (iron content analysis)\n- I₂ vs Na₂S₂O₃ (vitamin C determination)\n\n**Sources of Error:**\n1. **Air bubble** in burette tip\n2. **Overshooting endpoint** (add too fast)\n3. **Dirty glassware** (not rinsed)\n4. **Reading error** (parallax, meniscus)\n5. **Indicator choice** (wrong pH range)\n\n**Accuracy Tips:**\n- Read meniscus at eye level\n- Swirl constantly during titration\n- Add drop-wise near endpoint\n- Perform multiple titrations (average concordant results)\n- Use white tile under flask (see color change better)"
            }
        ],
        "exercises": []
    },

    {
        "id": "organic-chemistry-intro-sec4-chem",
        "title": "Introduction to Organic Chemistry",
        "title_zh": "有机化学导论",
        "gradeLevel": "sec4",
        "tag": "Chemistry",
        "tag_zh": "化学",
        "description": "Hydrocarbons, functional groups, and organic reactions",
        "description_zh": "碳氢化合物、官能团和有机反应",
        "objectives": [
            "Name and draw structures of organic compounds",
            "Identify functional groups and their properties",
            "Describe combustion, addition, and substitution reactions"
        ],
        "objectives_zh": [
            "命名并绘制有机化合物结构",
            "识别官能团及其性质",
            "描述燃烧、加成和取代反应"
        ],
        "sections": [
            {
                "id": "hydrocarbons",
                "type": "text",
                "title": "Hydrocarbons: Alkanes & Alkenes",
                "title_zh": "碳氢化合物：烷烃和烯烃",
                "content": "**Organic Chemistry** is the study of carbon-containing compounds.\n\n**Why Carbon is Special:**\n1. **Tetravalent:** Forms 4 bonds (C has 4 valence electrons)\n2. **Catenation:** Carbon atoms bond to each other → long chains, rings\n3. **Versatile:** Forms single, double, triple bonds\n4. **Basis of life:** DNA, proteins, carbohydrates, fats\n\n**Hydrocarbons** contain only carbon and hydrogen.\n\n**Alkanes** (Saturated Hydrocarbons)\n\n**General Formula:** CₙH₂ₙ₊₂\n\n**All single bonds** (C-C, C-H)\n\n**Homologous Series:**\n\n| n | Name | Formula | Structure |\n|---|------|---------|----------|\n| 1 | Methane | CH₄ | CH₄ |\n| 2 | Ethane | C₂H₆ | CH₃-CH₃ |\n| 3 | Propane | C₃H₈ | CH₃-CH₂-CH₃ |\n| 4 | Butane | C₄H₁₀ | CH₃-CH₂-CH₂-CH₃ |\n| 5 | Pentane | C₅H₁₂ | CH₃-CH₂-CH₂-CH₂-CH₃ |\n\n**Properties:**\n- Boiling point **increases** with chain length (stronger London forces)\n- **Non-polar** (low solubility in water)\n- **Unreactive** (strong C-C and C-H bonds)\n- Undergo **combustion** and **substitution**\n\n**Uses:**\n- **Methane:** Natural gas (cooking, power plants)\n- **Propane, Butane:** LPG (liquefied petroleum gas) for portable stoves\n- **Petrol (gasoline):** Mix of C₅-C₁₀ alkanes\n- **Diesel:** C₁₀-C₂₀ alkanes\n- **Singapore Petrochemicals:** Jurong Island refines and cracks hydrocarbons\n\n**Alkenes** (Unsaturated Hydrocarbons)\n\n**General Formula:** CₙH₂ₙ\n\n**At least one C=C double bond**\n\n**Homologous Series:**\n\n| n | Name | Formula | Structure |\n|---|------|---------|----------|\n| 2 | Ethene | C₂H₄ | CH₂=CH₂ |\n| 3 | Propene | C₃H₆ | CH₃-CH=CH₂ |\n| 4 | Butene | C₄H₈ | CH₃-CH₂-CH=CH₂ |\n\n**Properties:**\n- **More reactive** than alkanes (C=C is reactive site)\n- Lower boiling point than corresponding alkane\n- **Decolorize bromine water** (test for unsaturation)\n- Undergo **addition reactions**\n\n**Test for Unsaturation:**\nAdd **bromine water (brown)** to unknown hydrocarbon\n\n- **Alkene:** Br₂ decolorized (addition reaction)\n- **Alkane:** No change (no reaction)\n\n$$CH_2=CH_2 + Br_2 \\rightarrow CH_2Br-CH_2Br$$\n\n**Structural Isomers:**\nCompounds with **same molecular formula** but **different structures**\n\n**Example: C₄H₁₀**\n\n**1. Butane (straight chain):**\nCH₃-CH₂-CH₂-CH₃\n\n**2. Methylpropane (branched):**\n```\n    CH₃\n    |\nCH₃-CH-CH₃\n```\n\n**Different structures → different properties** (e.g., boiling points)\n\n**Fractional Distillation** (Crude Oil Refining)\n\nSeparates crude oil into fractions based on boiling points\n\n**Process at Singapore Refineries:**\n1. Crude oil heated in furnace\n2. Vapors rise up fractionating column\n3. Column cooler at top, hotter at bottom\n4. **Each fraction condenses** at different height\n\n**Fractions (bottom to top):**\n\n| Fraction | Carbon atoms | Boiling range | Uses |\n|----------|--------------|---------------|------|\n| Bitumen | > C₃₅ | > 400°C | Roads, waterproofing |\n| Fuel oil | C₂₀-C₃₅ | 350-400°C | Ships, power stations |\n| Diesel | C₁₀-C₂₀ | 250-350°C | Trucks, buses |\n| Kerosene | C₁₀-C₁₆ | 150-250°C | Jet fuel, heating |\n| Naphtha | C₆-C₁₀ | 60-150°C | Chemicals, petrochemicals |\n| Petrol | C₅-C₁₀ | 40-100°C | Cars |\n| LPG | C₃-C₄ | < 40°C | Portable fuel |\n| Refinery gas | C₁-C₂ | < 20°C | Fuel for refinery |\n\n**Cracking:**\nBreaking long-chain hydrocarbons into shorter, more useful ones\n\n**Thermal Cracking:**\nHigh temperature (700-900°C), high pressure\n\n$$C_{10}H_{22} \\rightarrow C_8H_{18} + C_2H_4$$\n(Decane → Octane + Ethene)\n\n**Catalytic Cracking:**\nLower temperature (450°C), zeolite catalyst\n\n**Products:**\n- Shorter alkanes (petrol, diesel)\n- Alkenes (plastics, polymers)\n\n**Why Crack?**\n- **Demand mismatch:** More demand for petrol than long chains\n- **Alkenes needed:** For plastic production (polymerization)\n\n**Singapore Petrochemical Complex (Jurong Island):**\n- ExxonMobil, Shell, Chevron refineries\n- Cracking produces ethene, propene\n- Used to make polyethene, polypropene (plastics)\n- Exports petroleum products regionally"
            },
            {
                "id": "functional-groups",
                "type": "text",
                "title": "Functional Groups & Organic Reactions",
                "title_zh": "官能团与有机反应",
                "content": "**Functional Groups** are specific atom arrangements that determine chemical properties.\n\n**Major Functional Groups:**\n\n**1. Alcohols (-OH)**\n\n**General Formula:** CₙH₂ₙ₊₁OH or R-OH\n\n**Examples:**\n- **Methanol:** CH₃OH (toxic, industrial solvent)\n- **Ethanol:** C₂H₅OH (drinking alcohol, biofuel)\n- **Propanol:** C₃H₇OH\n\n**Properties:**\n- **Polar** (O-H bond)\n- Hydrogen bonding → higher boiling point than alkanes\n- Soluble in water (small alcohols)\n- React with sodium (produce H₂ gas)\n\n**Test:** Add Na → fizzing (H₂ gas)\n$$2CH_3OH + 2Na \\rightarrow 2CH_3ONa + H_2$$\n\n**Uses:**\n- Ethanol: Alcoholic drinks, hand sanitizer (70%)\n- Methanol: Biodiesel production\n- Propanol: Industrial solvent\n\n**Singapore Context:**\n- Ethanol-based sanitizers (COVID-19 pandemic)\n- Biodiesel research (alternative to petroleum diesel)\n\n**2. Carboxylic Acids (-COOH)**\n\n**General Formula:** CₙH₂ₙ₊₁COOH or R-COOH\n\n**Examples:**\n- **Methanoic acid:** HCOOH (ant sting acid)\n- **Ethanoic acid:** CH₃COOH (vinegar, 5% solution)\n- **Propanoic acid:** C₂H₅COOH\n\n**Properties:**\n- **Weak acids** (partially ionize in water)\n- Sour taste\n- React with carbonates → CO₂ gas\n- React with alcohols → esters\n\n**Test:** Add Na₂CO₃ → fizzing (CO₂)\n$$2CH_3COOH + Na_2CO_3 \\rightarrow 2CH_3COONa + H_2O + CO_2$$\n\n**Uses:**\n- Ethanoic acid: Food preservative, vinegar\n- Citric acid: Soft drinks, food flavoring\n\n**3. Esters (-COO-)**\n\n**General Formula:** R-COO-R'\n\n**Formation (Esterification):**\n$$\\text{Carboxylic Acid} + \\text{Alcohol} \\xrightarrow{H_2SO_4} \\text{Ester} + \\text{Water}$$\n\n**Example:**\n$$CH_3COOH + C_2H_5OH \\xrightarrow{H_2SO_4} CH_3COOC_2H_5 + H_2O$$\n\n**Properties:**\n- **Sweet, fruity smells** (banana, pineapple, strawberry)\n- Volatile (low boiling points)\n- Insoluble in water\n\n**Uses:**\n- Food flavoring (artificial fruit flavors)\n- Perfumes, cosmetics\n- Solvents (nail polish remover)\n- Biodiesel (vegetable oil esters)\n\n**Singapore Applications:**\n- Food industry: Ester flavoring\n- Cosmetics manufacturing\n\n**Types of Organic Reactions:**\n\n**1. Combustion (Burning)**\n\n**Complete Combustion** (excess oxygen):\n$$\\text{Hydrocarbon} + O_2 \\rightarrow CO_2 + H_2O + \\text{Energy}$$\n\n**Example: Methane (Natural Gas)**\n$$CH_4 + 2O_2 \\rightarrow CO_2 + 2H_2O$$\n\n**Uses:**\n- Power generation (Singapore's power plants)\n- Heating (cooking gas)\n- Vehicle fuel\n\n**Incomplete Combustion** (limited oxygen):\n$$\\text{Hydrocarbon} + O_2 \\rightarrow CO + H_2O$$\n(or carbon/soot if very limited)\n\n**Danger:** Carbon monoxide (CO) is toxic (binds to hemoglobin)\n\n**2. Substitution (Alkanes)**\n\nReplacing one atom/group with another\n\n**Example: Chlorination of Methane**\n$$CH_4 + Cl_2 \\xrightarrow{UV light} CH_3Cl + HCl$$\n\n**Conditions:** UV light or sunlight\n\n**Uses:**\n- Making chlorinated solvents\n- Pesticide production\n\n**3. Addition (Alkenes)**\n\nAdding atoms across C=C double bond\n\n**Hydrogenation (+ H₂):**\n$$C_2H_4 + H_2 \\xrightarrow{Ni catalyst} C_2H_6$$\n\n**Uses:** Making margarine (solidify vegetable oils)\n\n**Hydration (+ H₂O):**\n$$C_2H_4 + H_2O \\xrightarrow{H_3PO_4 catalyst} C_2H_5OH$$\n\n**Uses:** Industrial ethanol production\n\n**Halogenation (+ Br₂):**\n$$C_2H_4 + Br_2 \\rightarrow C_2H_4Br_2$$\n\n**Uses:** Test for unsaturation (decolorizes bromine water)\n\n**4. Polymerization (Addition Polymers)**\n\nMany small molecules (monomers) join to form large molecule (polymer)\n\n**Example: Polyethene (Plastic Bags)**\n$$n(CH_2=CH_2) \\rightarrow (-CH_2-CH_2-)_n$$\n\n**Polypropene (Plastic Containers):**\n$$n(CH_2=CH-CH_3) \\rightarrow (-CH_2-CH(CH_3)-)_n$$\n\n**Poly(vinyl chloride) - PVC (Pipes):**\n$$n(CH_2=CHCl) \\rightarrow (-CH_2-CHCl-)_n$$\n\n**Singapore Plastics Industry:**\n- Jurong Island produces polymers\n- Plastic waste management challenges\n- Recycling initiatives (blue bins)\n- Biodegradable plastics research\n\n**5. Fermentation**\n\n**Making Ethanol from Glucose:**\n$$C_6H_{12}O_6 \\xrightarrow{yeast} 2C_2H_5OH + 2CO_2$$\n\n**Conditions:**\n- Temperature: 30-40°C\n- Anaerobic (no oxygen)\n- Yeast enzyme catalyst\n\n**Uses:**\n- Alcoholic beverages (beer, wine)\n- Biofuel (ethanol fuel)\n\n**Singapore:**\n- Limited fermentation industry (small scale)\n- Import most alcoholic beverages\n- Research on algae biofuels"
            }
        ],
        "exercises": []
    },

    {
        "id": "metals-reactivity-sec4-chem",
        "title": "Metals & Reactivity Series",
        "title_zh": "金属与活性系列",
        "gradeLevel": "sec4",
        "tag": "Chemistry",
        "tag_zh": "化学",
        "description": "Metal extraction, alloys, and displacement reactions",
        "description_zh": "金属提取、合金和置换反应",
        "objectives": [
            "Use reactivity series to predict reactions",
            "Explain metal extraction methods",
            "Describe properties and uses of alloys"
        ],
        "objectives_zh": [
            "使用活性系列预测反应",
            "解释金属提取方法",
            "描述合金的性质和用途"
        ],
        "sections": [
            {
                "id": "reactivity-series",
                "type": "text",
                "title": "Reactivity Series of Metals",
                "title_zh": "金属活性系列",
                "content": "**Reactivity Series** ranks metals by their tendency to lose electrons (form positive ions).\n\n**Order (most reactive to least):**\n\n**Mnemonic:** **P**lease **S**end **C**ats, **M**onkeys **A**nd **Z**ebras **I**n **T**iny **L**ittle **C**ages **H**aving **S**mall **G**reen **P**lants\n\n| Symbol | Metal | Reactivity |\n|--------|-------|------------|\n| **K** | Potassium | **Most Reactive** |\n| **Na** | Sodium | ↑ |\n| **Ca** | Calcium | |\n| **Mg** | Magnesium | |\n| **Al** | Aluminum | |\n| **Zn** | Zinc | |\n| **Fe** | Iron | |\n| **Sn** | Tin | |\n| **Pb** | Lead | |\n| **H** | (Hydrogen) | [reference] |\n| **Cu** | Copper | |\n| **Ag** | Silver | |\n| **Au** | Gold | **Least Reactive** ↓ |\n\n**Key Properties:**\n\n**More reactive metals:**\n- **Lose electrons more easily** (stronger reducing agents)\n- React more vigorously with water, acids, oxygen\n- Form more stable compounds\n- Harder to extract from ores\n\n**Less reactive metals:**\n- **Hold onto electrons** (weaker reducing agents)\n- Less reactive with water, acids\n- May occur as pure metals in nature (Au, Ag)\n- Easier to extract\n\n**Reactions to Compare Reactivity:**\n\n**1. Reaction with Water**\n\n**Very reactive (K, Na, Ca):**\n- React **vigorously** with cold water\n- Produce metal hydroxide + hydrogen\n\n$$2Na + 2H_2O \\rightarrow 2NaOH + H_2$$\n\n**Moderately reactive (Mg):**\n- Reacts **slowly** with cold water\n- Reacts **rapidly** with steam\n\n$$Mg + H_2O(steam) \\rightarrow MgO + H_2$$\n\n**Less reactive (Al, Zn, Fe):**\n- React only with **steam** (not cold water)\n\n$$3Fe + 4H_2O(steam) \\rightarrow Fe_3O_4 + 4H_2$$\n\n**Unreactive (Cu, Ag, Au):**\n- **No reaction** with water or steam\n\n**2. Reaction with Dilute Acids**\n\n**Above H in series:**\n- React with dilute acids (HCl, H₂SO₄)\n- Produce salt + hydrogen\n\n$$Zn + H_2SO_4 \\rightarrow ZnSO_4 + H_2$$\n$$Mg + 2HCl \\rightarrow MgCl_2 + H_2$$\n\n**Below H in series:**\n- **No reaction** with dilute acids\n\n**Test for H₂ gas:** Lighted splint → \"pop\" sound\n\n**3. Displacement Reactions**\n\n**More reactive metal** displaces **less reactive metal** from compound\n\n**Example:**\n$$Zn + CuSO_4 \\rightarrow ZnSO_4 + Cu$$\n\n- Zn is **more reactive** than Cu\n- Zn displaces Cu from copper sulfate\n- Blue CuSO₄ solution becomes colorless\n- Brown Cu metal forms\n\n**Another Example:**\n$$Fe + CuSO_4 \\rightarrow FeSO_4 + Cu$$\n\nBut:\n$$Cu + ZnSO_4 \\rightarrow \\text{NO REACTION}$$\n\n(Cu is less reactive than Zn)\n\n**4. Reaction with Oxygen (Air)**\n\n**Very reactive (K, Na):**\n- Tarnish **instantly** in air\n- Must be stored under oil\n\n$$4Na + O_2 \\rightarrow 2Na_2O$$\n\n**Moderately reactive (Mg, Al):**\n- React with oxygen, but Al forms **protective oxide layer**\n\n$$4Al + 3O_2 \\rightarrow 2Al_2O_3$$\n\n**Less reactive (Fe, Cu):**\n- React **slowly** with oxygen (rusting, tarnishing)\n\n$$4Fe + 3O_2 + 2xH_2O \\rightarrow 2Fe_2O_3 \\cdot xH_2O$$ (rust)\n\n**Unreactive (Au, Ag):**\n- **Do not tarnish** (Au) or tarnish very slowly (Ag)\n\n**Singapore Applications:**\n\n**Construction (HDB, MRT):**\n- Steel (Fe+C alloy) for structures\n- Corrosion protection needed\n- Galvanizing: Zinc coating on steel\n\n**Marine Environment:**\n- Ships, ports face corrosion\n- Use sacrificial anodes (Mg, Zn)\n\n**Electronics:**\n- Gold used in circuit boards (doesn't corrode)\n- Copper wiring (good conductor, relatively unreactive)\n\n**Jewelry:**\n- Gold, silver (don't tarnish)\n- Sterling silver: 92.5% Ag + 7.5% Cu\n\n**Industrial Uses:**\n- Aluminum: Drink cans, aircraft (light, oxide layer protects)\n- Zinc: Galvanizing steel, batteries\n- Iron/Steel: Construction, manufacturing"
            },
            {
                "id": "metal-extraction",
                "type": "text",
                "title": "Extraction of Metals",
                "title_zh": "金属提取",
                "content": "**Metal Extraction** is the process of obtaining pure metal from its ore.\n\n**Ore:** Rock containing enough metal compound to make extraction economical\n\n**Method depends on reactivity:**\n\n**Reactivity Principle:**\n- More reactive metal → more stable compound → harder to extract → more expensive\n\n**Extraction Methods:**\n\n**1. Native State (Au, Ag)**\n\n**Least reactive metals** found as pure elements\n\n**Method:** Physical separation (panning, sieving)\n\n**Example:** Gold nuggets in rivers\n\n**2. Heating Alone (Hg, Ag)**\n\n**Low reactivity** metals from oxides/sulfides\n\n**Example: Mercury from Cinnabar (HgS)**\n$$HgS + O_2 \\rightarrow Hg + SO_2$$\n\nHeat decomposes ore directly\n\n**3. Heating with Carbon (Fe, Zn, Sn, Pb)**\n\n**Moderate reactivity** (below Al, above Cu)\n\n**Carbon reduction** in blast furnace\n\n**Example: Iron from Hematite (Fe₂O₃)**\n\n**Blast Furnace Process:**\n\n**Inputs:**\n- Iron ore (Fe₂O₃)\n- Coke (carbon)\n- Limestone (CaCO₃)\n- Hot air\n\n**Reactions:**\n\n**Step 1:** Coke burns\n$$C + O_2 \\rightarrow CO_2$$\n\n**Step 2:** CO₂ reduced to CO\n$$CO_2 + C \\rightarrow 2CO$$\n\n**Step 3:** CO reduces iron ore\n$$Fe_2O_3 + 3CO \\rightarrow 2Fe + 3CO_2$$\n\n**Step 4:** Limestone removes impurities (SiO₂)\n$$CaCO_3 \\rightarrow CaO + CO_2$$\n$$CaO + SiO_2 \\rightarrow CaSiO_3$$ (slag)\n\n**Products:**\n- **Molten iron** (bottom, tapped off)\n- **Slag** (floats on iron, removed)\n- **Waste gases** (CO₂, N₂)\n\n**Singapore Context:**\nNo iron ore or blast furnaces, but imports steel for construction/manufacturing\n\n**4. Electrolysis (K, Na, Ca, Mg, Al)**\n\n**Most reactive metals** (above carbon in reactivity series)\n\n**Cannot be reduced by carbon** (too reactive)\n\n**Method:** Pass electricity through molten ore\n\n**Example: Aluminum from Bauxite (Al₂O₃)**\n\n**Process:**\n\n**Step 1: Purification**\nBauxite (Al₂O₃ + impurities) → Pure Al₂O₃\n\n**Step 2: Electrolysis**\n\n**Setup:**\n- Graphite electrodes\n- Molten cryolite (Na₃AlF₆) as solvent (lowers melting point)\n- Temperature: ~950°C\n\n**Reactions:**\n\n**Cathode (-):**\n$$Al^{3+} + 3e^- \\rightarrow Al$$ (reduction)\n\nMolten aluminum sinks to bottom\n\n**Anode (+):**\n$$2O^{2-} \\rightarrow O_2 + 4e^-$$ (oxidation)\n\nOxygen reacts with graphite anode:\n$$C + O_2 \\rightarrow CO_2$$\n\n**Anode needs regular replacement** (burns away)\n\n**Why Expensive?**\n- High electricity consumption\n- High temperature needed\n- Electrode replacement\n\n**Recycling aluminum saves 95% of energy!**\n\n**Singapore Aluminum Industry:**\n- No bauxite mines\n- Imports aluminum ingots\n- Manufacturing: Drink cans, window frames, aircraft parts\n- Recycling facilities (blue bins for aluminum cans)\n\n**Cost Comparison:**\n\n| Metal | Method | Relative Cost |\n|-------|--------|---------------|\n| Au | Physical separation | Low (if found) |\n| Fe | Carbon reduction | Medium |\n| Al | Electrolysis | High |\n| Na | Electrolysis | Very high |\n\n**Recycling Metals:**\n\n**Advantages:**\n1. **Energy savings** (e.g., Al: 95% less energy)\n2. **Conserve resources** (ores are finite)\n3. **Reduce waste** (landfill)\n4. **Less pollution** (no mining, smelting)\n5. **Economic** (cheaper than extraction)\n\n**Singapore Recycling:**\n- **Blue bins:** Paper, plastic, metal, glass\n- **Metal scrap yards:** Process for recycling\n- **Aluminum cans:** High recycling value\n- **E-waste:** Gold, copper from electronics\n- **Smart Nation:** Sensors to optimize collection\n\n**Environmental Impact:**\n\n**Mining:**\n- Habitat destruction\n- Soil erosion\n- Water pollution\n\n**Smelting:**\n- Air pollution (CO₂, SO₂)\n- Energy consumption\n- Waste slag\n\n**Solution:**\n- **Reduce:** Use less metal\n- **Reuse:** Repair, repurpose\n- **Recycle:** Process for reuse\n- **Replace:** Use alternatives (plastics, composites)"
            },
            {
                "id": "alloys",
                "type": "text",
                "title": "Alloys & Their Uses",
                "title_zh": "合金及其用途",
                "content": "**Alloy:** Mixture of two or more metals (or metal + non-metal)\n\n**Why Make Alloys?**\n\n**Pure metals often too:**\n- **Soft** (deform easily)\n- **Weak** (low tensile strength)\n- **Reactive** (corrode quickly)\n\n**Alloys are:**\n- **Stronger** (atoms of different sizes prevent layers sliding)\n- **Harder** (resist deformation)\n- **More resistant to corrosion**\n- **Can have special properties** (lower melting point, magnetic)\n\n**How Alloys Strengthen:**\n\n**Pure Metal:**\n- All atoms same size\n- Layers slide easily over each other\n- **Soft, malleable**\n\n**Alloy:**\n- Different-sized atoms\n- Layers cannot slide easily\n- **Harder, stronger**\n\n**Major Alloys:**\n\n**1. Steel (Iron + Carbon)**\n\n**Composition:** Fe + 0.1-2% C (+ other elements)\n\n**Types:**\n\n**Mild Steel:** 0.1-0.3% C\n- Soft, ductile, easily shaped\n- **Uses:** Car bodies, nails, wire, building structures\n- **Singapore:** HDB frames, MRT structures\n\n**Medium Steel:** 0.3-0.7% C\n- Harder, stronger\n- **Uses:** Tools, bolts, gears\n\n**High-Carbon Steel:** 0.7-1.5% C\n- Very hard, brittle\n- **Uses:** Cutting tools, drill bits, knives\n\n**Stainless Steel:** Fe + Cr (18%) + Ni (8%)\n- **Corrosion-resistant** (Cr forms protective oxide)\n- **Uses:** Cutlery, sinks, surgical instruments, building facades\n- **Singapore:** Changi Airport, Marina Bay Sands, hawker center tables\n\n**2. Brass (Copper + Zinc)**\n\n**Composition:** Cu (60-70%) + Zn (30-40%)\n\n**Properties:**\n- Golden color (decorative)\n- Good conductor\n- Corrosion-resistant\n- Harder than pure copper\n\n**Uses:**\n- Musical instruments (trumpets, saxophones)\n- Door handles, locks\n- Electrical connectors\n- Decorative items\n- Coins (Singapore 5¢, 10¢, 20¢ coins)\n\n**3. Bronze (Copper + Tin)**\n\n**Composition:** Cu (90%) + Sn (10%)\n\n**Properties:**\n- Harder than brass\n- Corrosion-resistant (especially seawater)\n- Easy to cast (statues, bells)\n\n**Uses:**\n- Marine parts (propellers, ship fittings)\n- Statues, bells\n- Coins (historically)\n- **Singapore:** Merlion statue contains bronze elements\n\n**4. Duralumin (Aluminum Alloy)**\n\n**Composition:** Al + Cu (4%) + Mg (1%) + Mn (0.5%)\n\n**Properties:**\n- Lightweight (like Al)\n- Much stronger than pure Al\n- Good conductor\n\n**Uses:**\n- **Aircraft bodies** (major use)\n- Bicycle frames\n- Fast trains\n- **Singapore:** Aircraft maintenance at Seletar Airport uses duralumin parts\n- **Changi Airport:** Aircraft industry\n\n**5. Solder (Tin + Lead or Lead-Free)**\n\n**Traditional:** Sn (60%) + Pb (40%)\n**Lead-free:** Sn + Cu + Ag (safer, required in many countries)\n\n**Properties:**\n- **Low melting point** (~180-190°C)\n- Good electrical conductor\n\n**Uses:**\n- Joining electrical components\n- Circuit boards\n- Plumbing (lead-free for water pipes)\n- **Singapore:** Electronics manufacturing (major industry)\n\n**6. Amalgam (Mercury + Other Metals)**\n\n**Dental Amalgam:** Hg + Ag + Sn + Cu\n\n**Properties:**\n- Soft when first mixed\n- Hardens in mouth\n- Durable\n\n**Uses:**\n- Tooth fillings (dental)\n- **Singapore:** Dental clinics use amalgam or newer composite materials\n\n**7. Cupronickel (Copper + Nickel)**\n\n**Composition:** Cu (75%) + Ni (25%)\n\n**Properties:**\n- Silver color\n- Corrosion-resistant (especially seawater)\n- Hard-wearing\n\n**Uses:**\n- Coins (Singapore 50¢, $1 coins)\n- Marine equipment\n- Desalination plants (Singapore's NEWater, Tuas Desalination Plant)\n\n**Smart Alloys:**\n\n**Shape Memory Alloys (e.g., Nitinol: Ni-Ti)**\n- \"Remember\" original shape\n- Return to shape when heated\n- **Uses:** Medical stents, orthodontic braces, eyeglass frames\n\n**Singapore Context:**\n\n**Construction:**\n- Steel (HDB, MRT, bridges)\n- Stainless steel (facades, fittings)\n- Aluminum alloys (window frames)\n\n**Transport:**\n- Duralumin (aircraft at Changi Airport)\n- Steel (MRT trains, ships)\n- Brass/bronze (marine fittings)\n\n**Electronics:**\n- Solder (circuit boards)\n- Copper alloys (connectors)\n- Gold alloys (contacts)\n\n**Coins:**\n- 5¢, 10¢, 20¢: Brass\n- 50¢, $1: Cupronickel\n\n**Advantages of Alloys Over Pure Metals:**\n\n| Property | Pure Metal | Alloy |\n|----------|------------|-------|\n| Strength | Low | High |\n| Hardness | Low | High |\n| Corrosion resistance | Variable | Better |\n| Melting point | Fixed | Adjustable |\n| Cost | Higher (pure) | Lower (bulk) |\n| Uses | Limited | Versatile |\n\n**Summary:**\nAlloys are essential for modern technology and construction. Singapore, though it has no metal ores, is a major user and processor of alloys in electronics, construction, and aerospace industries."
            }
        ],
        "exercises": []
    },

